training_organizations.name: Wyoming DFS – Child Protection Training
training_organizations.description: The Wyoming Department of Family Services provides training for its Protective Services workers as part of a small, centralized system. New CPS workers usually go through initial training at the DFS Social Services Academy, which covers Wyoming’s policies, safety assessment models, and investigative techniques, often with assistance from neighboring states’ resources due to Wyoming’s size. Ongoing training is offered online or regionally, given Wyoming’s rural spread, to reinforce skills like interviewing children and case documentation.

training_organizations.name: CASA of Wyoming (local CASA programs)
training_organizations.description: Wyoming utilizes Court Appointed Special Advocates in several jurisdictions (e.g., CASA of Laramie County, CASA of Natrona County). These local nonprofits train community volunteers to act as CASAs:contentReference[oaicite:54]{index=54}, who are then appointed by judges to advocate for children in abuse/neglect cases. Each CASA volunteer conducts independent fact-finding and provides the court with recommendations on the child’s best interests, ensuring that even in Wyoming’s often under-resourced courts, children have a dedicated advocate. The state doesn’t have a single unified CASA program, but these local programs collectively contribute to child advocacy in the court system.

training_organizations.name: Wyoming Citizen Review Panel
training_organizations.description: A federally mandated but community-run panel that examines the effectiveness of Wyoming’s child protective services. Composed of citizen volunteers, including professionals and concerned residents, the panel reviews CPS policies, case summaries, and outcomes to evaluate whether the state is meeting its child protection responsibilities. It issues recommendations to DFS for improvements (for example, suggesting better training or policy changes). While not a service provider, this independent oversight role by an NGO-type body is an important part of Wyoming’s CPS system, adding transparency and public input into child welfare operations.
